AUDIO: 'Hello everyone and welcome back to Vitello University. Today we\'re going to be going over how to make great window pulls inside of Vitello or the best practices to get the best window pulls. Today\'s agents want to give you a good'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'view of the outside and a good view of the inside, so let\'s talk about how we can get that. You don\'t need to spend hours in post-production. You should just be able to upload it to Vitello and it give you back a great result. So'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to step-by-step look at just the settings and general rules that you can go over to get that great result. I have a selection of window pull examples. I\'m going to go into camera raw and then we\'ll go over the settings'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in which I took them just so you can see. A couple examples are going to be just straight ambient with a 5-2 bracket and then I\'m going to show you how ambient can help you and then I\'m going'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to show you what not to do whenever you see something called window bloom in the field. First, we\'ll start with the settings for a 5-2 bracket or a 3-2 bracket depending on what your needs'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are. So if you take a look at this one, I did five shots all handheld. The ISO needs to be as low as it can be in whatever setting you\'re in. If it is a darker house, you can go up to like 800'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all the way up to 3200 in some cameras. It just depends on your actual equipment, but you know, do a test to find out what your limits are in your actual camera. So the ISO for this shot'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is 1600. I shot it with a 12 to 24 at 12. I was at F5.6 and the starting shot for this, which the scene is actually a little bit too'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dark, was 6400. But just so I could stop for a second, I was in aperture priority. So the camera actually chose what it needed to see so it could get the correct brackets. If you set your'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aperture priority, average metering, and then your ISO to just a base setting, so I would normally start at about 320 ISO and go up from there. If you go any lower or any'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'higher, you may get some long shutter drag at the very end on those shorter durations, and that may give a little bit of camera shake if you\'re doing it handheld, and I wouldn\'t want to do that.'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
