AUDIO: 'and then in the other one, you can see the interior clearly with all of the different colors and everything. The middle is just going to give us more dynamic range in the actual processing. Whenever you upload into Photello, it'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually reprocesses it and gives it more dynamic range that they can work with in the end. So, taking a look at these window pulls, if you really wanted to, you could come in and out and look at more, but we\'re just going to take a'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at how it would be uploaded to Photello itself, which we always suggest just putting the raw JPEGs, not the raw files, straight from your camera into Photello without any post-processing.'

[03:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, to get the best window pulls, you\'re just wanting to see the outside, which this would be perfectly fine. If it was a brighter scene or a different type of scene, you may have to go one more stop'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to see outside the windows, but this is a rare situation whenever the sun is going to be coming directly in, and you need that 6,400ths of a second. This is a perfect 5-2 set to see everything that'

[03:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you would need and in this particular scene you would really only need the 3-2. So, this for the windows, this for the interior. And that\'s all you would need. This is going to be called a'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flambiant shot. And that\'s flash and ambient together to give you one cohesive look. So, right now you can see with this one there is tiny little bits of window bloom coming out here. And so,'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the only way to combat that would be either getting more frames like I showed you before, taking another 5-2 bracket, or using some type of flash. So, the flash is important, but it doesn\'t'

[04:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'necessarily need to be a big extravagant flash most of the time. So, let\'s take a look at the settings. I was at ISO 200 on that 12-24 again. This time I was at 4.5 cuz it is a darker scene. So,'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whenever I set it to aperture priority, it started the scene at a 30th of a second and then it went to an 8th of a second, which would be tough to do handheld. So, we are on a tripod.'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'With the tripod, the image doesn\'t move. So, I have the trigger on top of the camera. And so, whenever I\'ve done those two, I then turn it on and then that tells the flash to fire. So, it fires'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I point it directly behind me and that lights up the scene in front of me. And that\'s called bounce flash. So, with the bounce flash we can see'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that it gave a real nice crisp views of all the windows the way it can pull out in fotello so we can see through it. So, in this scene we had that little bit'

[05:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
